Decision and Reasoning Justiciar:

Decision of the Justiciar:   FALSE (reversing the original Judgement)

Rule 1596 begins:

      A Payment Order is an order requiring an entity (the payor) to
      submit a Transfer Order transferring units of a Currency from
      itself to some other entity (the payee).  A Payment Order
      specifies exactly one source entity, exactly one destination
      entity, exactly one Currency, and a number of units of that
      Currency which is a positive multiple of that Currency's MUQ.

The question is whether one could devise something that is unambiguously
(but not explicitly) an order, requiring a specified entity to submit a TO
for a specified amount of currency from itself to another specified entity,
_without_ explicitly and unambiguously stating that the purported Payor is
ordered to effect a payment as a consequence of that message.  I believe we
can.

Any ambiguity in the payee, payor, or amount of currency fails the Rule's
requirement that these are "specified".   "The Bank is ordered to pay
Player X" is not sufficient (though this sentence could possibly be part of
a complete and valid PO).  But if I say that "I order the Bank to pay 1 VT
to Player X," that is explicit and is a Payment Order, assuming I had
authority to issue it.

Suppose we do not _explicitly_ state that the Bank is commanded to effect a
payment as a consequence.  If the Speaker says "Player X is awarded one VT
from the Bank, for meritorious conduct," then this alone is not
unambiguously an order and on its own would not be a PO.  (As others have
pointed out, it could just be an observation.)

However, this sentence together with other text could be an order.  Suppose
the Speaker posts a message consisting of

        --------------------------------------------
                      OFFICIAL NOTICE
                    Speaker's Patronage

        Player X is awarded one VT from the Bank,
        for meritorious conduct.
        --------------------------------------------

Surely in the old days the person responsible for recording VTs would have
treated this entire message as an order and felt required to act upon it.
It unambiguously (but not explicitly) requires the Bank to pay a specified
amount of currency to a specified player, and nowadays that will mean
issuing a Transfer Order. Thus it satisfies all the requirements for a PO.

This is sufficient to determine the decision, so I will not lengthen this
decision by considering Blots.  But I will say that these are a thorny
issue involving interactions of rules, and the question of whether an order
can "specify" things like payees, payors, and amounts, by having the
players delve into various Rules to determine them.  It is not clear.

Regards,
-- elJefe, Justiciar

